snippet.textDisplay:
Alex, the best way to tap a hole is to chuck the tap and turn the speed all the way down. Then Unlock the quill, apply light down pressure and blip the spindle on and off until the tap grabs. Once the tap is started, unchuck it, put a tap handle on it and finish tapping it by hand, turning the tap backwards a little bit every half turn or so to break off the chip. This insures that you get a true start to your threads on the mill but you don't break taps. The threads just come out cleaner this way too.

Also use conventional milling on a manual mill has more to do with accuracy then not launching your parts.
snippet.textOriginal:
Alex, the best way to tap a hole is to chuck the tap and turn the speed all the way down. Then Unlock the quill, apply light down pressure and blip the spindle on and off until the tap grabs. Once the tap is started, unchuck it, put a tap handle on it and finish tapping it by hand, turning the tap backwards a little bit every half turn or so to break off the chip. This insures that you get a true start to your threads on the mill but you don't break taps. The threads just come out cleaner this way too.

Also use conventional milling on a manual mill has more to do with accuracy then not launching your parts.

snippet.textDisplay:
16:16 You didn't read the instructions to that indicator. That's not a 2 way indicator, as you can see from the little lever under the dial. That means the indicator will only deflect in one direction. And not the other.

You need an 2 way indicator that will deflect in both directions. Then preload the indicator, then check it.

If you're trying to mill something, for machinists sake, use the power feed, rather than hand feeding it like crazy...

Please go and get a lesson or a short course in basic machining.

No feeds and speeds is not just guessing.
